 thousands of Mexicans to perform physical labor in the United States between 1942 and 1964 in exchange for remittances sent back to Mexico. As partners and family members were dispersed across national borders, interpersonal relationships were transformed. The prolonged absences of Mexican workers, mostly men, forced women and children at home to inhabit new roles, create new identities, and cope with long-distance communication from fathers, brothers, and sons. Drawing on an extraordinary range of sources, Ana Elizabeth Rosas uncovers a previously hidden history of transnational family life. Intimate and personal experiences are revealed to show how Mexican immigrants and their families were not passive victims but instead found ways to embrace the spirit (abrazando el espíritu) of making and implementing difficult decisions concerning their family situations—creating new forms of affection, gender roles, and economic survival strategies with long-term consequences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFamilieszMexicoxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aFamilieszMexicoy20th century. 0aForeign workers, MexicanxFamily relationshipszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrant familieszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aMexicanszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aMigrant agricultural laborersxFamily relationshipszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh  a20th century american history.  aaffection.  aamerican crossroads series.  aamerican immigration.  abracero program.  aeconomic struggles.  afamily situations.  afamily.  afarm workers.  afarming.  agender roles.  ahistory.  aimmigration.  ainterpersonal relationships.  alabor history.  alabor.  along distance communication.  alow wage farmers